      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The argument that congestion pricing is a regressive tax is often a valid critique, as the fee disproportionately affects low-income drivers who lack alternatives to driving. However, framing the opposition solely as an attempt to block environmental progress ignores the fact that many communities near the city center are already marginalized and would bear the brunt of the costs even without the tax. Proponents argue that the revenue generated can be directly reinvested into public transit and to provide rebates for the most affected residents, effectively making the system progressive in its long-term impact. Ultimately, the debate hinges on whether the city can implement fair exemptions and redistribution mechanisms to ensure the plan doesn't punish the poor while still achieving its environmental goals.",
